page.title: 11NATURAL HISTORY TREDIS
page.content: DESPITE INTENSIVE AGRICULTURE THE AREA RETAINS A GREAT SPECIES RICHNESS BECAUSE OF THE RANGE OF HABITATS PRESENT.TO THE SOUTH ARE THE UNCULTIVATABLE CLIFFLANDS WITH FULMAR PEREGRINE & DARTFORD WARBLER,WHILE TO THE NORTHEAST IS THE ESTUARY AND SALTINGS SUPPORTING LITTLE GREBE, SPOONBILL,CANADA GEESE, DUNLIN, REDSHANK & OTHER WADERS. THE FARM LAND BETWEEN IS POOR IN TREE COVER BUT REDSTART,FIRECREST,SISKIN & HAWFINCH ARE NOTED.AMONG THE UNUSUAL SIGHTINGS ARE THE HOOPOE (a migrant) AND THE GLOSSY STARLING (probably an escape). THE BARN OWL & LITTLE OWL ARE DECREASING BUT THE COLLARED DOVE CONTINUES TO INCREASE.GREATER CHICKWEED IS MORE COMMON THAN RECORDED.RED DATA BOOK SPECIES,THE SLENDER BIRD'S FOOT TREFOIL & THE CARROT BROOMRAPE ARE IN THE SSSI.
